    <text>
        <body>
            <head>91. Personal Note Prepared by the Deputy Secretary of State (<persName
                    corresp="recrWcRZxYT57GiP4">Dam</persName>)<note n="1" place="foot"
                    type="source" xml:id="d91fn1">Source: Department of State, Executive
                    Secretariat, <gloss target="#t_SSI_1">S/S–I</gloss> Records: Deputy Secretary
                        <persName corresp="recrWcRZxYT57GiP4">Dam</persName>’s Official Files, Lot
                    85D308, Personal Notes of Deputy Secretary—Kenneth W. <persName
                        corresp="recrWcRZxYT57GiP4">Dam</persName>—Oct. 1983–Sept. 1984. Secret.
                    Dictated on March 30.</note>
            </head>
            <opener>
                <dateline rendition="#right">
                    <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1984-03-30"
                        >March 30, 1984</date>
                </dateline>
            </opener>
            <p>I attended a meeting of the <orgName corresp="recxTfPOTDKnnC576">Senior Arms Control
                    Policy Group</orgName> this afternoon at 4:30.<note n="2" place="foot"
                    xml:id="d91fn2">No formal minutes were found.</note> The subject was continued
                work on <gloss target="#t_INF_1">
                    <rs type="event" corresp="recgLCwFE47waxYP9">INF</rs>
                </gloss> and <gloss target="#t_START_1">
                    <rs type="event" corresp="recGzN4S83GSdMO7O">START</rs>
                </gloss>. The way we are putting this is that we want to have our options clearly
                delineated so that we will be in a position to negotiate in the event that the
                Soviets express an interest in returning to either talks. There seems no possibility
                that they will be prepared to return to the <gloss target="#t_INF_1">
                    <rs type="event" corresp="recgLCwFE47waxYP9">INF</rs>
                </gloss> talks as such, but it does seem that they have dug themselves something of
                a hole by saying they won’t return to the <gloss target="#t_START_1">
                    <rs type="event" corresp="recGzN4S83GSdMO7O">START</rs>
                </gloss> talks until we withdraw the <gloss target="#t_INF_1">
                    <rs type="compound-subject" corresp="recvy4qghNg7RFWmN">INF</rs>
                </gloss> missiles from <placeName corresp="recp8rWUqC6nWf8T5">Europe</placeName>.
                The <persName corresp="rec5PPNCl6qqfgBAq">President</persName> has authorized some
                probing of the Soviets on <gloss target="#t_START_1">
                    <rs type="event" corresp="recGzN4S83GSdMO7O">START</rs>
                </gloss>, including the possibility of being able to lay out to them what we have in
                mind when we say we would be prepared to discuss trading off areas of advantage to
                us for areas of advantage to them.<note n="3" place="foot" xml:id="d91fn3">See <ref
                        target="#d90">Document 90</ref>.</note> Thus we now have a green light to do
                additional work in both areas, but the work on <gloss target="#t_START_1">
                    <rs type="event" corresp="recGzN4S83GSdMO7O">START</rs>
                </gloss> is what is particularly important. In addition, we are looking at ways in
                which <gloss target="#t_INF_1">
                    <rs type="event" corresp="recgLCwFE47waxYP9">INF</rs>
                </gloss> might be brought into the <gloss target="#t_START_1">
                    <rs type="event" corresp="recGzN4S83GSdMO7O">START</rs>
                </gloss> negotiations in some fashion, <pb facs="0367" n="338" xml:id="pg_338"/> not
                necessarily by means of the so-called “merger” about which there has been so much
                public discussion.</p>
            <p>I attended a meeting in <persName corresp="rece7NCQ7Hh9DICyN">the
                    Secretary</persName>’s office at the end of the day in preparation for his
                meeting with <persName corresp="rec62rNu2glRunbNq">Dobrynin</persName> next week. We
                now have had an exchange of letters between <persName corresp="rec5PPNCl6qqfgBAq"
                    >the President</persName> and <persName corresp="recDLz6e8cyqZjyPQ"
                    >Chernenko</persName>,<note n="4" place="foot" xml:id="d91fn4">Scheduled for
                    publication in <ref target="frus1981-88v04#d190">
                        <hi rendition="simple_italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1981–1988, vol. IV,
                        Soviet Union, January 1983–March 1985, Documents 190</ref> and <ref
                        target="frus1981-88v04#d197">197</ref>.</note> and that leaves the
                possibility of some progress in discussions between the <placeName
                    corresp="recxXt2KOngYAhHuL">U.S.</placeName> and the <placeName
                    corresp="rec7g4kEoiXWBjoX3">Soviet Union</placeName>, and the purpose of the
                discussion with <persName corresp="rec62rNu2glRunbNq">Dobrynin</persName> next week
                will be to explore how our talks can be moved ahead. One can say that outside of the
                nuclear area, there is a good deal going on, including <gloss target="#t_CDE_1">
                    <rs type="event" corresp="recbuYyghGC9TqlrN">CDE</rs>
                </gloss>, <gloss target="#t_MBFR_1">
                    <rs type="event" corresp="recd0oQmzEzecymcf">MBFR</rs>
                </gloss> and <rs corresp="rectadvRz4QZmc1z7" type="topic">chemical weapons</rs>, as
                well as boundary talks in the <placeName corresp="rec5FoMP88jchHZtK">Bering
                    Sea</placeName>, upgrade of the <rs type="topic" corresp="recDL8PkwumuVDX1o">hot
                    line</rs>, consulates, <rs type="compound-subject" corresp="rec1KH4XsybSRdEWc"
                    >exchanges</rs> (which was previously called “<rs type="compound-subject"
                    corresp="rec1KH4XsybSRdEWc">cultural agreement</rs>”), and other related
                areas.</p>
            <p>[Omitted here are discussions not related to <gloss target="#t_START_1">
                    <rs type="event" corresp="recGzN4S83GSdMO7O">START</rs>
                </gloss>.]</p>
        </body>
